Inorder Traversal: 1 3 4 6 7 8 10 13 14
```

Sure, here's a JavaScript function that takes a callback function as an argument and returns a button element that supports dragging and dropping an image onto it:


```javascript
function createDragAndDropButton(callback) {
 const button = document.createElement('button');
 button.textContent = 'Drag and drop an image here';

 button.addEventListener('dragover', e => {
 e.preventDefault();
 button.classList.add('dragover');
 });

 button.addEventListener('dragleave', () => {
 button.classList.remove('dragover');
 });

 button.addEventListener('drop', e => {
 e.preventDefault();
 button.classList.remove('dragover');

 const file = e.dataTransfer.files[0];
 const reader = new FileReader();
 reader.readAsDataURL(file);

 reader.onload = () => {
 const img = new Image();
 img.src = reader.result;

 img.onload = () => {
 const div = document.createElement('div');
 div.style.width = `${img.naturalWidth}px`;
 div.style.height = `${img.naturalHeight}px`;
 div.style.position = 'relative';

 const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
 canvas.width = img.naturalWidth;
 canvas.height = img.naturalHeight;
 div.appendChild(canvas);

 const svg = document.createElementNS('http://www.w3.org/2000/svg', 'svg');
 svg.setAttribute('width', `${img.naturalWidth}px`);
 svg.setAttribute('height', `${img.naturalHeight}px`);
 svg.style.position = 'absolute';
 svg.style.top = '0';
 svg.style.left = '0';
 div.appendChild(svg);

 const context = canvas.getContext('2d');
 context.drawImage(img, 0, 0);

 let isDrawing = false;
 let lastX = 0;
 let lastY = 0;

 function draw(x, y) {
 if (!isDrawing) return;
 const path = document.createElementNS('http://www.w3.org/2000/svg', 'path');
 path.setAttribute('d', `M ${lastX} ${lastY} L ${x} ${y}`);
 path.setAttribute('stroke', 'black');
 path.setAttribute('stroke-width', '2');
 path.setAttribute('fill', 'transparent');
 svg.appendChild(path);
 lastX = x;
 lastY = y;
 }

 svg.addEventListener('mousedown', e => {
 isDrawing = true;
 lastX = e.offsetX;
 lastY = e.offsetY;
 });

 svg.addEventListener('mousemove', e => {
 draw(e.offsetX, e.offsetY);
 });

 svg.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
 isDrawing = false;
 });

 callback(div);
 };
 };
 });

 return button;
}
```
This function creates a button element with the text "Drag and drop an image here" and adds event listeners to support dragging and dropping an image onto it. When an image is dropped onto the button, it creates a div element of the same size as the image's natural width and height, with a canvas element containing the image data, and an SVG element overlaid onto the image. The function also adds event listeners to the SVG element to allow the user to draw on top of the image using the mouse. When an image is dropped onto the button, it calls the callback function with the created div element as an argument.

In JavaScript and React, you can use the `sessionStorage` or `localStorage` API to save data in the browser's storage.

The `sessionStorage` object stores data for the duration of the browser session, while the `localStorage` object stores data indefinitely until it is cleared by the user or the browser.

Here is an example implementation in React using `sessionStorage`:


```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function Conversations() {
 const [page, setPage] = useState(1);

 useEffect(() => {
 // Get the current page number from sessionStorage
 const storedPage = sessionStorage.getItem('page\_number');

 // Use the stored page number if it exists
 if (storedPage) {
 setPage(parseInt(storedPage));
 }
 }, []);

 const handlePageChange = (newPage) => {
 // Save the new page number to sessionStorage
 sessionStorage.setItem('page\_number', newPage);

 // Update the current page state
 setPage(newPage);
 }

 // Fetch conversations based on the current page number
 const conversations = fetchConversations(page);

 return (
 <div>
 <ConversationList conversations={conversations} />
 <Pagination page={page} onPageChange={handlePageChange} />
 </div>
 );
}
```
In this example, the current page number is stored in the `page` state variable using the `useState` hook. The `useEffect` hook is used to retrieve the stored page number from `sessionStorage` and update the `page` state when the component mounts.

When the user changes the page number, the `handlePageChange` function is called, which saves the new page number to `sessionStorage` using `sessionStorage.setItem('page_number', newPage)`.

Finally, the `conversations` are fetched based on the current page number and rendered using the `ConversationList` and `Pagination` components.

This is just a simple example, and the exact implementation will depend on your specific use case and framework. However, the basic idea is to use the browser's storage API to store user-specific data, such as the current page number, for each user session.

If you want to reset the page number to 0 every time the user navigates away from the app and then comes back, you can use the `sessionStorage` or `localStorage` API to store a flag that indicates whether the user has left the app or not. Here's an example implementation in React:


```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function Conversations() {
 const [page, setPage] = useState(0);

 useEffect(() => {
 // Check if the user has left the app
 const hasLeftApp = sessionStorage.getItem('has\_left\_app');

 if (hasLeftApp) {
 // If the user has left the app, reset the page number to 0
 sessionStorage.setItem('has\_left\_app', false);
 setPage(0);
 } else {
 // If the user has not left the app, get the current page number from sessionStorage
 const storedPage = sessionStorage.getItem('page\_number');
 if (storedPage) {
 setPage(parseInt(storedPage));
 }
 }
 }, []);

 const handlePageChange = (newPage) => {
 // Save the new page number to sessionStorage
 sessionStorage.setItem('page\_number', newPage);
 setPage(newPage);
 }

 // Fetch conversations based on the current page number
 const conversations = fetchConversations(page);

 // Add an event listener to detect when the user leaves the app
 useEffect(() => {
 const handleVisibilityChange = () => {
 if (document.visibilityState === 'hidden') {
 // If the user leaves the app, set the 'has\_left\_app' flag to true
 sessionStorage.setItem('has\_left\_app', true);
 }
 }

 document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', handleVisibilityChange);

 return () => {
 document.removeEventListener('visibilitychange', handleVisibilityChange);
 }
 }, []);

 return (
 <div>
 <ConversationList conversations={conversations} />
 <Pagination page={page} onPageChange={handlePageChange} />
 </div>
 );
}
```
In this example, the `useEffect` hook is used to check if the `has_left_app` flag is set in `sessionStorage`. If it is set to `true`, it means the user has left the app and the current page number should be reset to 0. The flag is then reset to `false`.

If the `has_left_app` flag is not set, the current page number is retrieved from `sessionStorage` as before.

The `handleVisibilityChange` function is added as an event listener to the `visibilitychange` event. This event is fired when the user navigates away from the app or switches to another tab. If the `visibilityState` is `hidden`, it means the user has left the app, and the `has_left_app` flag is set to `true`.

