```
html<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
 <meta charset="utf-8">
 <title>Pannellum Viewer</title>
 <style>
 html, body {
 margin: 0;
 padding: 0;
 width: 100%;
 height: 100%;
 }
 #panorama {
 width: 100%;
 height: 100%;
 }
 </style>
 <script src="https://cdn.pannellum.org/2.5/pannellum.js"></script>
 <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.pannellum.org/2.5/pannellum.css">
</head>
<body>
 <div id="panorama"></div>

 <script>
 // Get the panorama URL from the query parameter
 var urlParams = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
 var panoramaUrl = urlParams.get('panorama');

 // Set the title of the web page to the file name of the panorama
 var title = panoramaUrl.split('/').pop().split('.')[0].replace(/([a-z])([A-Z])/g, '$1 $2').replace(/([A-Z])([A-Z][a-z])/g, '$1 $2');
 document.title = title;

 // Load the panorama using Pannellum
 pannellum.viewer('panorama', {
 "type": "equirectangular",
 "panorama": panoramaUrl,
 "autoLoad": true
 });
 </script>
</body>
</html>
```
In this code, we're using JavaScript to extract the file name of the panorama from the URL, remove the extension, and add spaces between words based on changes in case. We're then setting the resulting string as the title of the web page using the `document.title` property.

Note that this code assumes that the file name of the panorama is included in the URL passed as the `panorama` query parameter. If the file name is not included in the URL, or is included in a different format, you may need to modify the regular expressions used to extract and format the file name.

